2 SENATE BILL 39
1 methodology; requiring the Department to increase the Maryland Medical
2 Assistance Program reimbursement rate for outpatient mental health centers by a
3 certain percentage in certain fiscal years; and generally relating to certified
4 community behavioral health clinics and outpatient mental health centers
5 behavioral health rate methodology modernization.
6 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
7 Article – Health – General
8 Section 16–201.3(e) and (h)
9 Annotated Code of Maryland
10 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
11 BY adding to
12 Article – Health – General
13 Section 7.5–211 and 15–160
14 Annotated Code of Maryland
15 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
16 Preamble
17 WHEREAS, The State has operated certified community behavioral health clinics
18 (CCBHC) under limited federal grant funding since 2018, serving thousands of State
19 residents with integrated mental health and substance use care; and
20 WHEREAS, The CCBHC model has demonstrated improvements in access, care
21 coordination, health outcomes, and reductions in emergency department utilization and
22 inpatient stays; and
23 WHEREAS, The State must move from a grant–funded pilot approach to CCBHCs
24 to a sustainable statewide model with a clear rate methodology, ensuring that behavioral
25 health providers can continue to deliver high–quality, evidence–based, value–driven care;
26 and
27 WHEREAS, Outpatient mental health centers (OMHC) are a cornerstone of the
28 State’s behavioral health system, providing community–based treatment for individuals
29 with serious mental health conditions; and
30 WHEREAS, OMHCs are in financial crisis due to inadequate and outdated
31 reimbursement rates that fail to reflect the true cost of service delivery, workforce needs,
32 and compliance requirements; and
33 WHEREAS, The State currently lacks a formal, transparent rate–setting
34 methodology for OMHCs and CCBHCs, leading to inconsistent and unsustainable
35 reimbursement practices; and

SENATE BILL 39 3
1 WHEREAS, The closure of OMHCs, such as in Frederick County, demonstrates the
2 urgent risk to access and continuity of care across the State if rate inadequacies remain
3 unaddressed; and
4 WHEREAS, The General Assembly recognizes the importance of establishing parity
5 between behavioral health and somatic health services, including through transparent,
6 cost–driven rate reform; now, therefore,
7 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
8 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
9 Article – Health – General
10 16–201.3.
11 (e) (1) IN THIS SUBSECTION, “COMMISSION” MEANS THE MARYLAND
12 HEALTH CARE COMMISSION.
